          "Body": "A monk in the abbey at Brünn (modern Brno) in Czechoslovakia, Mendel experiments with pea plants in his garden. Crossing varieties with different characters, such as smooth or wrinkled seed cases, he discovers that in most cases characters do not blend, but continue to appear in subsequent generations in predictable ratios. He finds that ‘dominant’ characters will appear even if inherited from only one parent, while offspring show ‘recessive’ characters only if they inherit them from both parents. He publishes his work in the journal of his local natural history society, but its significance will not be widely recognised until after his death.",
